english:
  title: Letter to Attendant-at-Law Lee Regarding His Preface
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I bow my head before you, Gentleman Lee.

    Yesterday I received the preface you graciously composed for my collected works, and my joy and gratitude know no bounds. For what we call a preface to a collection is the herald of that entire work—it draws forth and unfolds the essence hidden within the author's heart, serving as the very standard by which all else is measured. This is why the ancients deemed no collection complete without a preface.

    My son Ham, having gathered my poems and prose into a complete collection, asked me: "Now that the work is finished, should we not crown it with a preface? Who would be worthy?" I answered him as a teacher might: "Only Gentleman Lee knows my heart and understands my poetry. Who else could I entrust with this task?" My son took my words to heart, and soon your pearls of wisdom adorned the opening pages, gleaming with such brilliance. Your prose shines with such luminous grace, your words so finely wrought, that they illuminate my humble writings and magnify my name far beyond what a simple man like me deserves to receive.

    Consider the precedents: Li Yangbing was the uncle of the great Li Bai, and Li Han was the son-in-law of the eminent Han Yu. When they wrote prefaces for their relatives' works, neither could escape whispers of favoritism. Yet Li Bai and Han Yu were talents of such supreme excellence that even when praised to the heavens—Li Bai as one who stands alone across the centuries, Han Yu as one who embodies both the feelings of Zhou and the wisdom of Confucius—the world felt no sense of impropriety, only that such praise fell short of their true merit.

    You and I share no such family bond, so there can be no question of bias. If we were to speak with perfect objectivity, my writings should be diminished rather than exalted, criticized rather than elevated. Yet how could a preface that disparages what it introduces make any sense? For your sake, it would suffice to explain merely the origins and development of the collection itself. Why then embellish with excessive praise, lifting me to stand beside the immortal chariots of Li Bai and Han Yu? Would this not be a grave offense against propriety? Surely others must harbor doubts.

    Ah, but Yangbing and Li Han, though related by blood, escaped the world's suspicion precisely because they could remain impartial toward their kinsmen. You, though unrelated to me, seem unable to escape the suspicion of others—and this is because you have shown kindness to one distant from you. The burden I have placed upon you runs so deep that what more can I say?

    Yet should my poems and prose, by virtue of your preface, endure beyond my lifetime, that would be the greatest honor. How could I fail to hold this in my heart?

    Since receiving your preface, illness has prevented me from offering timely thanks. I am filled with shame and contrition. I bow again and submit this with utmost respect.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Li Yangbing (李陽冰): Tang Dynasty calligrapher and relative of the poet Li Bai, known for preserving Li Bai''s literary legacy.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Li Han (李漢): Son-in-law of the great Tang prose master Han Yu, who wrote a preface for Han Yu''s collected works.'
  - key: ''
    value: '''Thousand-years standing alone'' (千載獨步): A phrase expressing unparalleled excellence across centuries.'
  - key: ''
    value: '''Zhou''s feelings and Confucian thoughts'' (周情孔思): A reference to the depths of Han Yu''s wisdom and moral philosophy.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Wu Yan (無鹽) and Momo (嫫母): Legendary figures representing ugliness in classical Chinese literature—here used metaphorically to suggest the author''s own modest abilities.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Li Taibai (李太白) and Han Tuizhi (韓退之): Respectful appellations for Li Bai and Han Yu, representing the highest pinnacle of Chinese literary achievement.'
